issue_body:
It's impossible to inherit from the Faker class due to bad metaclass magic;

```py
class Faker2(Faker):
    pass

  File "/vagrant/server/app/api/tests.py", line 44, in <module>
    class Faker2(Faker):
TypeError: Error when calling the metaclass bases
    first argument must be callable
```

Current code does not define `NGLModel`.

Add model (for what?)

```javascript
var NGLModel = widgets.DOMWidgetModel.extend({
    defaults: function(){
        return _.extend(widgets.DOMWidgetModel.prototype.defaults(), {
            _model_name: 'NGLModel',
            _model_module: 'nglview-js-widgets',
            _model_module_version: require("../package.json").version,
        });
    }
})
```

However, this cause lots of lagging in frontend (due to validation?).

## Expected Behavior
We used [this code](https://github.com/davisking/dlib/blob/master/tools/archive/train_face_5point_model.cpp) that you used for the 5-point facial landmark shape prediction. We've used the 5-point training data and annotated three additional points: left-mouth, right-mouth and chin. We modified the code that flips the dataset to look like:
```
template <
    typename image_array_type,
    typename T
    >
void add_image_left_right_flips_8points (
    image_array_type& images,
    std::vector<std::vector<T> >& objects
)
{
    // make sure requires clause is not broken
    DLIB_ASSERT( images.size() == objects.size(),
        "\t void add_image_left_right_flips()"
        << "\n\t Invalid inputs were given to this function."
        << "\n\t images.size():  " << images.size() 
        << "\n\t objects.size(): " << objects.size() 
        );

    typename image_array_type::value_type temp;
    std::vector<T> rects;

    const unsigned long num = images.size();
    for (unsigned long j = 0; j < num; ++j)
    {
        const point_transform_affine tran = flip_image_left_right(images[j], temp);

        rects.clear();
        for (unsigned long i = 0; i < objects[j].size(); ++i)
        {
            rects.push_back(impl::tform_object(tran, objects[j][i]));

            DLIB_CASSERT(rects.back().num_parts() == 8); //<--This line was changed
            swap(rects.back().part(0), rects.back().part(2));
            swap(rects.back().part(1), rects.back().part(3));
           swap(rects.back().part(5), rects.back().part(6)); //<---We added this line for the mouth
        }

        images.push_back(temp);
        objects.push_back(rects);
    }
}
```

We expected to get ballpark the same training time as for the 5-point (around 30 hours) with the same setup.

## Current Behavior
What we found was that the training was virtually brought a halt (1400 hours estimate). The function that was to blame is found in `randomly_generate_split_feature` in `shape_predictor_trainer.h`. One iteration takes anything between one second to five seconds, which is in a tight loop.

When we comment out the flipping and rotation, the training time is ballpark correct (5 hours). When either flipping or rotation is added it becomes impossibly slow.

We then used `imglab`'s own rotation and flipping (the new one) and used that, which then brought us back to 34 hours.

Also retraining the 5-point with flipping/rotation trains within 30 hours.

## Steps to Reproduce
* Use [this code](https://github.com/davisking/dlib/blob/master/tools/archive/train_face_5point_model.cpp) with the two modifications (cassert for 8 points and flipping the labels of the mouth) also available with the manifests below
* Use the 5-point training data [here](http://dlib.net/files/data/dlib_faces_5points.tar) with [these](https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/18u4dsULeqHRN7Wr9jyNqu1NhPkxkU15S?usp=sharing) xml manifests.
* Observe slowness

* **Version**: 19.9
* **Where did you get dlib**: built from source from github releases
* **Platform**: `Ubuntu 17.10 x64 on Intel i7`
* **Compiler**: `gcc (Ubuntu 7.2.0-8ubuntu3) 7.2.0`

## Remarks
I'm not sure if it is essentially a problem/bug or if there may be something wrong with the flipping/rotation. It might be due to the randomness?

We would also like to contribute the following if you are interested
- The 8-point annotations
- The trained model (imglab flipped/rotated)

